+{"id":"frankentorch-sirh","title":"tensor_diagonal is severed-autograd: linear backward (inverse of diag_embed)","description":"tensor_diagonal at lib.rs:8232 extracts the diagonal of a 2-D matrix (with optional offset). The forward is purely linear in the input: output[i] = input[row_start + i, col_start + i]. PyTorch's torch.diagonal is differentiable.

Backward (the inverse of diag_embed):
   grad_input[row_start + i, col_start + i] = grad_output[i]
   grad_input is zero elsewhere.

Wrap the F64 path in tensor_apply_function with this analytical backward. F32 path keeps the existing fail-loud behavior to preserve dtype semantics (consistent with the affine_grid / linalg_inv pattern). Surfaced during /reality-check pass.","notes":"Fixed in this commit. Wrapped the F64 path of tensor_diagonal in tensor_apply_function with the inverse-of-diag_embed backward: grad_input[row_start + i, col_start + i] = grad_output[i], all other positions 0. F32 path adds an explicit fail-loud guard for requires_grad=true (consistent with affine_grid / linalg_inv pattern; tensor_apply_function is f64-only). Captured (m, n, row_start, col_start, diag_len) via closure. Added diagonal_propagates_gradient_via_scatter_to_diag_positions regression test (3x3 main diagonal under sum loss → grad = identity matrix, asserts to 1e-12). ft-api lib tests: 1149.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-30T18:33:10.136220810Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-30T18:35:08.689447318Z","closed_at":"2026-04-30T18:35:08.687012453Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"frankentorch-skpl","title":"Implement tensor_triangular_solve autograd [child of tw0y]","description":"Wrap tensor_triangular_solve in tensor_apply_function with the analytical backward.
For X = A^{-1} B (A triangular):
   grad_B = A^{-T} grad_X = triangular_solve(A^T, grad_X, !upper)
   grad_A = -A^{-T} grad_X X^T   masked to triangular pattern of A
The grad_A computation can either reuse triangular_solve(A^T, grad_X, !upper) for the leading factor and then outer-product with X^T, or compute the n×n result directly. Either way, save A and X for backward.

Note: detach A's gradient from non-triangular positions — PyTorch returns 0 in those positions. The mask (upper or lower triangle) must match the input convention.","notes":"Fixed in this commit. Wrapped tensor_triangular_solve in tensor_apply_function with the analytical backward grad_B = A^{-T} grad_X (via inline triangular_solve on A^T with !upper) and grad_A = -A^{-T} grad_X X^T masked to A's triangle. A and X are saved for backward. Added triangular_solve_propagates_gradient_through_a_and_b regression test (diagonal A, lower triangle, sum loss → analytical [[-2.5, 0], [-1.25, -1.25]] for grad_A, [0.5, 0.25] for grad_B). ft-api lib tests: 1141.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-30T18:07:27.992618763Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-30T18:09:33.402153177Z","closed_at":"2026-04-30T18:09:33.398938832Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
